/lib/python3.14/site-packages/gi/_gi.cpython-314-x86_64-linux-gnu.so\n    _function_info_vectorcall (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/python3.14/site-packages/gi/_gi.cpython-314-x86_64-linux-gnu.so\n    _PyEval_EvalFrameDefault\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    _PyEval_Vector (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    PyEval_EvalCode\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    run_mod.lto_priv.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    pyrun_file.lto_priv.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    _PyRun_SimpleFileObject (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    _PyRun_AnyFileObject (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    Py_RunMain\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    Py_BytesMain\n      in /usr/lib/libpython3.14.so.1.0\n    __libc_start_call_main (/usr/src/debug/glibc/glibc/csu/../sysdeps/nptl/libc_start_call_main.h:58)\n      in /usr/lib/libc.so.6\n    __libc_start_main\n      in /usr/lib/libc.so.6\n```\n\n</details>\n\n\nAnyway, this is hard for me to understand, except that the leak generally has something to do with dbus. I'm currently trying [memray](https://bloomberg.github.io/memray), which seems to have support for combined python & native stack traces, but it will be a while until I see the results.\n\nHmm, tray is fairly simple and pretty much only listens to org.blueman.Applet with one or more dbus proxies. Which blueman version are you running this on?\nReproduced on both 2.4.6-2 from the Arch Linux repos, and on 202152648b4942dd536d7e60b89a356d5a344861 when running from source with `PATH=\"$PWD/apps:$PATH\" BLUEMAN_SOURCE=1 ./apps/blueman-applet`\nmy mistake, I'm not sure where I got \"blueman-tray\". Looking at my shell history, I've been looking at \"blueman-applet\" this whole time.\nmemray looks and works really nice for me. It has a nice live tui when run with `--live`.\n\nI noticed this just now, what the hell pulseaudio plugin \ud83d\udc40 .\n<img width=\"1332\" height=\"129\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/130feaa2-d173-4cac-9be3-a4c388b1c4c0\" />\nLooks like that pulseaudio space [isn't supposed to take up real memory, just virtual memory](https://man.archlinux.org/man/extra/libpulse/pulse-client.conf.5.en#shm_size_bytes=). But in practice it does seem to be using real memory:\n\n```\n\u276f grep '65536' -A 24 /proc/$(pgrep blueman-tray)/smaps\nSize:              65536 kB\nKernelPageSize:        4 kB\nMMUPageSize:           4 kB\nRss:               39764 kB\nPss:               39764 kB\nPss_Dirty:         39716 kB\nShared_Clean:          0 kB\nShared_Dirty:          0 kB\nPrivate_Clean:        48 kB\nPrivate_Dirty:     39716 kB\nReferenced:        35036 kB\nAnonymous:         39764 kB\nKSM:                   0 kB\nLazyFree:              0 kB\nAnonHugePages:         0 kB\nShmemPmdMapped:        0 kB\nFilePmdMapped:         0 kB\nShared_Hugetlb:        0 kB\nPrivate_Hugetlb:       0 kB\nSwap:              25772 kB\nSwapPss:           25772 kB\nLocked:                0 kB\nTHPeligible:           1\nProtectionKey:         0\nVmFlags: rd wr mr mw me ac sd\n```\n\nCould be worth making a bug report about, although personally I don't care since my OS can move it to swap if I have memory pressure.\n\n---\n\nAnyway, my latest trace doesn't seem to have given me useful results. When observed, blueman-applet is doing fine, and blueman-tray is acting up:\n\n<img width=\"955\" height=\"77\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/adf9c934-79d9-4d03-a2fb-89b5f14db078\" />\n\nI did discover that memray [has a live attach/detach mode](https://bloomberg.github.io/memray/attach.html), so I've done that and will see the results over the next while:\n\n```\npython3 -m memray attach 1684264 --verbose --native --compress-on-exit --output memray-1684264.out\n```\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Python comes with tracemalloc https://docs.python.org/3/library/tracemalloc.html. But I'll be honest I never used it and done much memory leak hunting in general. So hopefully @cschramm can correct me or give better guidance.\n\nHopefully the below is helpful.\n\nblueman-applet which is in the bin directory is a simple wrapper around the main Gtk.Application you find in the blueman/main directory. Which under the hood uses a GLib event loop.\n\nThe bulk of the moving parts I think are the proxies and objectmanagers you see in blueman/bluez. These are used all over the place. In the past we had issues with older versions of the proxies which went (mostly?) away when I turned them into singletons. Now I kinda regret this as it most likely just hid the issues, but it solved the issue we had at that moment so yeah.\n\nThe applet also creates a dbus service that handles some of the communication with BlueZ plus internal communication for other apps like the manager and tray.\n\nAnother point you might want to check are applet plugins you're using, like autoconnect. See if disabling them makes it go away of reduces the leaks.\n\nI will be experimenting with tracemalloc as I always wanted to see and understand better how blueman handles memory. So hopefully I can offer better assistance in these types of issues in the future.\nI will give tracemalloc a try, I didn't realize it had `tracemalloc.Snapshot.dump()` available. That's exactly what I wanted to be able to do, to compare heap dumps separated by a long time.\n\nI also noticed that kdeconnect is also leaking memory despite being a Qt app and not a GTK app like blueman. But I wonder if it could be a common component somehow. At one point, I remember installing some kind of theming system for both GTK and Qt, and while I'm not using it anymore, I wonder if some vestige remains and is causing problems.\n\nAnyway, I'll see. I don't expect this to be a rapid process given the rate of the leaks. I appreciate your through response and will dig into the code if this current approach doesn't work out.\nI instrumented blueman-tray, but the python heap didn't grow above a handful of megabytes.\n\nI then instrumented native memory allocations with `sudo heaptrack -p 470943`. Unfortunately, I didn't have required debug symbols active while tracing, but I was able to look these up after the fact [with quick script, resolve_symbols.py](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/25075996/resolve_symbols.py): `heaptrack_print -l -n 10 heaptrack.blueman-tray.1512568.zst | ./resolve_symbols.py --pid 470943 > resolved-leaks.txt`\n\n<details>\n\n```\nMEMORY LEAKS\n301.53M leaked over 451736470 calls from\ng_malloc\n  in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n76.25M leaked over 1079308 calls from:\n    g_variant_new_preallocated_trusted (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    g_variant_new_string\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    parse_value_from_blob.isra.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    parse_value_from_blob.isra.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    parse_value_from_blob.isra.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    parse_value_from_blob.isra.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    g_dbus_message_new_from_blob\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    _g_dbus_worker_do_read_cb (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    g_task_return_now (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    complete_in_idle_cb (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    g_main_dispatch (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    g_main_context_iterate_unlocked.isra.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    g_main_loop_run\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    gdbus_shared_thread_func.lto_priv.0 (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libgio-2.0.so.0\n    g_thread_proxy (:?)\n      in /usr/lib/libglib-2.0.so.0\n    start_thread (/usr/src/debug/glibc/glibc/nptl/pthread_create.c:448)\n      in /usr/lib/libc.so.6\n    __GI___clone3 (/usr/src/debug/glibc/glibc/misc/../sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/x86_64/clone3.S:78)\n      in /usr/lib/libc.so.6\n55.05M leaked over 743880 calls from:\n    g_variant_new_preallocated_trusted (:?)\n      